@rustbot label: +perf-regression-triaged

Did some investigation about the macro testing (which was maybe an oversight on my part), but it looks like regressions could not have occured: ([play](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2024&gist=1c8567f44989bae374a3bb0c27563f51))

```rust
macro_rules! a {
    ($i:item) => { $i };
    (const $i:item) => { $i }
}

a! {
    const impl A {}
}
```

Can't work since we still treat `const` as the start of an item (const item).

Note: This fails to parse `const unsafe impl … {}` (while `unsafe impl const … {}` does parse). We need to add another hack to the "fn frontmatter" check like we had to do for `const unsafe trait … {}` (PR #147864).

```rs
#![feature(const_trait_impl)]

const unsafe trait Trait {}

//unsafe impl const Trait for () {} // OK

const unsafe impl Trait for () {} //~ ERROR expected one of
```

CC meta issue https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/146122 in which I call for a rewrite of the way we parse item+type+bound+expr qualifiers+modifiers (I'm still experimenting on the side, see https://github.com/fmease/rasur).

Let's revert this quickly, to undo the impact on CI times.

Discussion of potential fixes and remaining concerns can happen on the reapply PR.

@bors r+ p=6

